===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|fro|avis}}, from the phrase ''ce m'est a vis'' ("in my view"), where {{m|fro|vis}} is from {{der|en|la|visus}}, past participle of {{m|la|videre||to see}}. See {{m|en|vision}}, and confer {{m|en|avise}}, {{m|en|advise}}. The unhistoric -d- was introduced in English 15c. {{doublet|en|aviso}}.

